The Greenland Shark , also known as small head sleeping shark , is widely distributed in Greenland and Iceland in the North Atlantic waters ; these sharks can reach 4 to 5 meters long as adults .
But their growth rate is extremely slow , sometimes only about 1 cm a year , suggesting that Greenland sharks may have an extremely long lives .
Traditional aging methods usually uses animal &apos;s calcification , and with regard to sharks we can use fins , but this kind of calcified tissue is very scarce in Greenland sharks .
A new study led by Julius Nelson of the University of Copenhagen ， Denmark resorted to the use of Greenland shark &apos;s ocular lens for radioactive carbon dating .
This methodology had previously been used to validate the age of whales , but it is the first time for it to be applied in sharks and other fish .
Their analysis shows that age estimate of the largest shark is 392 years old with a margin of error of 120 years .
